   <abstract>Exploring the Central Conservatory of Music (CCOM)'s Standard Grade Examination System for Violin, this thesis delves into its establishment, structure, and impact on music education in China. Initiated in 1992 by CCOM's Academic Committee, the system involves a Grade Examination Committee comprising professors from diverse music disciplines, aimed at evaluating students' musical proficiency through standardized graded examinations. Authored by Weijian Zhao, a former CCOM violin professor, the first edition of the violin examination book was published in 1993, gaining widespread adoption as the primary resource for violin grade examinations in China. Through a comprehensive examination framework, encompassing foundational skills, repertoire comprehension, and musicianship, the system provides students with valuable performance opportunities and constructive feedback from judges. Despite criticisms and challenges, including parental pressure and stress on students, based on the analysis of the materials, the system has significantly contributed to the development of young violin learners' musical abilities and continues to shape music education practices in China.</abstract>
